{
  "Surface ocean currents are primarily driven by:": "",
  "Volcanic activity on the ocean floor": "",
  "Differences in water density": "",
  "Global wind patterns": "",
  "Tidal forces from the Moon": "",
  "Surface ocean currents are primarily driven by prevailing global wind patterns such as the trade winds, westerlies, and polar easterlies. These persistent winds push the surface water and set large-scale circulation patterns in motion.": "",
  "Large circular current systems found in each major ocean basin are called:": "",
  "Tsunamis": "",
  "Gyres": "",
  "Eddies": "",
  "Tidal bores": "",
  "Gyres are large, circular ocean current systems that rotate clockwise in the Northern Hemisphere and counterclockwise in the Southern Hemisphere. There are five major gyres across the world's ocean basins.": "",
  "The Coriolis effect causes ocean currents in the Northern Hemisphere to curve:": "",
  "To the left": "",
  "Straight toward the equator": "",
  "Directly downward into the deep ocean": "",
  "To the right": "",
  "The Coriolis effect, caused by Earth's rotation, deflects moving objects to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere. This deflection is a key factor in shaping the circular patterns of ocean gyres.": "",
  "The Gulf Stream is a warm ocean current that flows along the eastern coast of:": "",
  "Australia": "",
  "South America": "",
  "Africa": "",
  "North America": "",
  "The Gulf Stream is a powerful, warm ocean current that originates in the Gulf of Mexico and flows northward along the eastern coast of North America before crossing the Atlantic Ocean toward Europe. It significantly moderates the climate of western Europe.": "",
  "Deep ocean currents are primarily driven by:": "",
  "Earthquakes on the ocean floor": "",
  "Wind patterns at the surface": "",
  "Tidal forces": "",
  "Differences in water temperature and salinity (density)": "",
  "Deep ocean currents, also called thermohaline circulation, are driven by differences in water density caused by variations in temperature and salinity. Cold, salty water is denser and sinks, while warmer, less salty water rises, creating a global conveyor belt of deep water movement.": "",
  "Upwelling occurs when:": "",
  "Ocean water evaporates and rises into the atmosphere": "",
  "Cold, nutrient-rich water rises from the deep ocean to the surface": "",
  "Warm surface water sinks to the ocean floor": "",
  "Two warm currents collide and push water upward": "",
  "Upwelling is the process by which cold, nutrient-rich deep water rises to the ocean surface. It is often driven by winds that push surface water away from the coast, allowing deeper water to move up and replace it, which supports highly productive ecosystems.": "",
  "Which of the following is true about warm ocean currents?": "",
  "They flow from tropical regions toward the poles and warm nearby coasts": "",
  "They cool nearby coastal climates": "",
  "They flow from polar regions toward the equator": "",
  "They only exist in the Pacific Ocean": "",
  "Warm ocean currents carry heated water from tropical regions toward the poles. As they flow along coastlines, they transfer heat to the atmosphere, warming the nearby land areas and moderating coastal climates.": "",
  "During an El Nino event, the trade winds in the Pacific Ocean:": "",
  "Weaken or reverse direction": "",
  "Strengthen significantly": "",
  "Stop completely and permanently": "",
  "Shift from east-west to north-south": "",
  "During an El Nino event, the normal easterly trade winds weaken or even reverse direction across the tropical Pacific. This allows warm surface water to spread eastward, suppressing upwelling along the South American coast and disrupting global weather patterns.": "",
  "The global thermohaline circulation pattern is often referred to as the:": "",
  "Atlantic Trade Route": "",
  "Pacific Ring of Fire": "",
  "Polar Express Current": "",
  "Great Ocean Conveyor Belt": "",
  "The thermohaline circulation is commonly called the Great Ocean Conveyor Belt because it functions like a continuous loop, transporting warm surface water toward the poles where it cools, becomes denser, sinks, and then flows back as cold deep water across the ocean basins.": "",
  "Cold ocean currents flowing along a coast tend to produce what type of climate nearby?": "",
  "Extremely cold with heavy snowfall": "",
  "Cool and dry": "",
  "Warm and rainy": "",
  "Hot and humid": "",
  "Cold ocean currents cool the air above them, which reduces evaporation and moisture in the atmosphere. This leads to cooler temperatures and drier conditions along nearby coastlines, which is why many coastal deserts are located alongside cold currents.": "",
  "What is a gyre?": "",
  "A deep-sea trench where water spirals downward": "",
  "A giant whirlpool that forms during hurricanes": "",
  "A type of ocean wave caused by earthquakes": "",
  "A large, circular system of ocean currents driven by wind patterns and the Coriolis effect": "",
  "A gyre is a large, circular system of ocean surface currents formed by the interaction of global wind patterns, the Coriolis effect, and continental landmasses. The five major gyres (North Atlantic, South Atlantic, North Pacific, South Pacific, and Indian Ocean) dominate ocean circulation.": "",
  "What does 'thermohaline circulation' mean?": "",
  "Ocean circulation driven by wind and tides": "",
  "The circular movement of water in a single ocean basin": "",
  "Circulation caused by underwater volcanic heating": "",
  "Deep ocean circulation driven by differences in water temperature and salinity": "",
  "Thermohaline circulation is the global deep-ocean circulation pattern driven by differences in water density, which is controlled by temperature ('thermo') and salinity ('haline'). Cold, salty water sinks at the poles and slowly flows through the deep ocean basins.": "",
  "What is the Coriolis effect?": "",
  "The gravitational pull of the Moon on ocean water": "",
  "The apparent deflection of moving objects caused by Earth's rotation": "",
  "The heating of ocean water by underwater volcanic vents": "",
  "The reflection of sunlight off the ocean surface": "",
  "The Coriolis effect is the apparent deflection of moving objects, including ocean currents and winds, caused by Earth's rotation. Objects are deflected to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere.": "",
  "What is upwelling?": "",
  "The upward movement of magma beneath the seafloor": "",
  "The swelling of ocean waves during a storm": "",
  "The rising of cold, nutrient-rich deep water to the ocean surface": "",
  "The evaporation of warm water from the ocean surface": "",
  "Upwelling is an oceanographic process in which cold, nutrient-rich water from the deep ocean rises to the surface. It typically occurs along coastlines where winds push surface water offshore, and the resulting nutrient supply supports abundant marine life.": "",
  "What does 'Ekman transport' refer to?": "",
  "The shipping of goods across the ocean along major trade routes": "",
  "The movement of icebergs from polar regions to warmer latitudes": "",
  "The transport of sediment along the ocean floor by deep currents": "",
  "The net movement of surface water at a right angle to the wind direction due to the Coriolis effect": "",
  "Ekman transport is the net movement of ocean surface water roughly 90 degrees to the right of the wind direction in the Northern Hemisphere (and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere) due to the Coriolis effect. This process is a key driver of coastal upwelling.": "",
  "What is El Nino?": "",
  "A permanent warm current in the Indian Ocean": "",
  "A periodic warming of surface waters in the central and eastern tropical Pacific Ocean": "",
  "A cold water event that causes heavy snowfall in South America": "",
  "A massive underwater volcanic eruption in the Pacific": "",
  "El Nino is a climate pattern characterized by the periodic warming of sea surface temperatures in the central and eastern tropical Pacific Ocean. It occurs when trade winds weaken, disrupting normal ocean circulation and causing widespread changes in weather patterns around the globe.": "",
  "What is La Nina?": "",
  "A period of unusually cool sea surface temperatures in the central and eastern tropical Pacific": "",
  "A period of unusually warm water temperatures in the Atlantic Ocean": "",
  "A type of ocean wave that forms during earthquakes": "",
  "A warm current that flows south along the coast of California": "",
  "La Nina is the counterpart to El Nino, characterized by cooler-than-normal sea surface temperatures in the central and eastern tropical Pacific Ocean. It occurs when trade winds strengthen, enhancing upwelling of cold deep water and influencing global weather patterns.": "",
  "What does 'downwelling' mean in ocean science?": "",
  "The evaporation of ocean water during a heat wave": "",
  "The movement of water horizontally along the ocean floor": "",
  "The decrease in wave height as storms move away": "",
  "The sinking of warm or dense surface water to deeper ocean layers": "",
  "Downwelling is the process by which surface water sinks to deeper ocean layers, often where currents converge or where water becomes denser due to cooling or increased salinity. It carries oxygen-rich surface water to the deep ocean but is typically less biologically productive than upwelling zones.": "",
  "What is a western boundary current?": "",
  "A current that only flows westward across the Atlantic Ocean": "",
  "A cold current that flows along the western coasts of continents": "",
  "A current formed by river water entering the ocean on western coastlines": "",
  "A narrow, fast, deep, warm current that flows along the western side of ocean basins": "",
  "Western boundary currents are narrow, fast, deep, and warm ocean currents that flow poleward along the western edges of ocean basins. Examples include the Gulf Stream in the Atlantic and the Kuroshio Current in the Pacific. They are intensified by the Coriolis effect.": "",
  "What does 'ENSO' stand for?": "",
  "Equatorial Northern Salinity Overlap": "",
  "Evaporative Nutrient Supply Operation": "",
  "Eastern North Sea Oscillation": "",
  "El Nino-Southern Oscillation": "",
  "ENSO stands for El Nino-Southern Oscillation, which is the coupled ocean-atmosphere climate pattern in the tropical Pacific that cycles between warm (El Nino) and cool (La Nina) phases. It is one of the most important drivers of year-to-year global climate variability.": "",
  "Fishermen off the coast of Peru notice that their fish catches have dropped dramatically during a particular year, and the sea surface is much warmer than usual. Which ocean phenomenon is most likely responsible?": "",
  "An El Nino event that suppressed coastal upwelling": "",
  "A major underwater earthquake": "",
  "The formation of a new ocean gyre": "",
  "A sudden increase in thermohaline circulation speed": "",
  "During an El Nino event, weakened trade winds reduce the upwelling of cold, nutrient-rich deep water along the Peruvian coast. Without these nutrients, phytoplankton populations decline, which collapses the food chain and causes fish catches to drop dramatically.": "",
  "A city in England is located at the same latitude as parts of Canada, yet it has much milder winters. Which ocean current is most responsible for warming this city's climate?": "",
  "The California Current": "",
  "The Gulf Stream and its extension, the North Atlantic Drift": "",
  "The Benguela Current": "",
  "The Labrador Current": "",
  "The Gulf Stream carries warm water from the tropical Atlantic northeastward, and its extension, the North Atlantic Drift, brings this warmth to the coasts of western Europe. This warm current releases heat into the atmosphere, giving cities in England and western Europe significantly milder winters than regions at similar latitudes in North America.": "",
  "A scientist drops a floating buoy into the ocean near the equator in the Pacific. Over several months, the buoy drifts westward. Which wind system is most likely driving the surface current that carries this buoy?": "",
  "The polar easterlies": "",
  "Local sea breezes": "",
  "The prevailing westerlies": "",
  "The northeast and southeast trade winds": "",
  "The trade winds blow from east to west near the equator, pushing surface ocean water westward across the tropical Pacific. These winds are the primary drivers of the equatorial surface currents that would carry the buoy in a westward direction.": "",
  "Researchers studying the Atacama Desert in Chile, one of the driest places on Earth, note that a cold ocean current flows just offshore. How does this cold current contribute to the extreme dryness?": "",
  "The cold current absorbs all the rain clouds from the sky": "",
  "The cold current creates strong winds that blow all clouds away from the coast": "",
  "The cold current cools the air above it, reducing evaporation and suppressing the formation of rain clouds": "",
  "The cold current freezes all moisture in the air before it reaches land": "",
  "The cold Humboldt (Peru) Current cools the air directly above it, which limits evaporation and stabilizes the lower atmosphere. This suppresses the formation of rain-producing clouds, contributing to the extreme aridity of the Atacama Desert along the Chilean coast.": "",
  "A team of climate scientists discovers that a large volume of freshwater from melting Arctic ice has entered the North Atlantic. They are concerned this could weaken thermohaline circulation. Why would added freshwater have this effect?": "",
  "Freshwater reacts with salt to produce a gas that blocks ocean circulation": "",
  "Freshwater is warmer than seawater and would heat the deep ocean": "",
  "Freshwater increases the Coriolis effect, which slows down all currents": "",
  "Freshwater lowers the salinity and density of surface water, reducing its ability to sink": "",
  "Thermohaline circulation depends on cold, salty surface water becoming dense enough to sink in the North Atlantic. An influx of freshwater from melting ice reduces the salinity and density of this water, potentially preventing it from sinking and weakening the entire global conveyor belt circulation.": "",
  "A satellite image shows a large patch of floating plastic debris accumulated in the center of the North Pacific Ocean. Which feature of ocean circulation best explains why debris collects there?": "",
  "Deep thermohaline currents push debris upward into one spot": "",
  "Strong tidal currents concentrate debris during spring tides": "",
  "The rotating currents of the North Pacific Gyre trap floating debris in its calm center": "",
  "A massive upwelling zone pushes debris to the surface": "",
  "The Great Pacific Garbage Patch forms in the calm center of the North Pacific Gyre, where the rotating circular currents converge and trap floating debris. The inward-spiraling surface currents carry plastic and other floating waste toward the center where water movement is minimal.": "",
  "An oceanographer observes that wind is blowing steadily from north to south along the western coast of a continent in the Southern Hemisphere. Based on Ekman transport, which direction will surface water move?": "",
  "Toward the shore (eastward)": "",
  "Straight downward into the deep ocean": "",
  "Away from the shore (westward, into the open ocean)": "",
  "Northward, opposite to the wind": "",
  "In the Southern Hemisphere, Ekman transport moves surface water 90 degrees to the left of the wind direction. With wind blowing southward along a western coast, the net water transport would be westward (away from shore), which would trigger coastal upwelling as deep water rises to replace it.": "",
  "A coastal community experiences unusually heavy rainfall and flooding during winter. Weather experts attribute the conditions to an El Nino event. The community is most likely located in:": "",
  "The western coast of South America (e.g., Peru or Ecuador)": "",
  "Northern Europe": "",
  "The eastern coast of Australia": "",
  "The Arctic coast of Russia": "",
  "During El Nino, warm surface water shifts eastward across the Pacific, bringing increased moisture and rainfall to the normally arid western coast of South America. Countries like Peru and Ecuador often experience heavy rains and flooding during strong El Nino events.": "",
  "A marine biologist notices that a region along the California coast has extremely high phytoplankton productivity. After investigating, she finds that deep, cold water is rising to the surface there. What process explains both the cold water and the high productivity?": "",
  "Thermohaline circulation depositing warm nutrients from the tropics": "",
  "El Nino warming the surface and promoting algal growth": "",
  "Coastal upwelling bringing nutrient-rich deep water to the sunlit surface": "",
  "Downwelling concentrating organisms into a small area": "",
  "Coastal upwelling along the California coast brings cold, nutrient-rich deep water to the surface where sunlight is available for photosynthesis. These nutrients fuel phytoplankton blooms, which form the base of a highly productive marine food web in the region.": "",
  "A student builds a model of ocean circulation in a large tank. She heats water at one end and cools it at the other end while adding salt to the cold water. She observes that the cold salty water sinks and flows along the bottom toward the warm end. What type of ocean circulation is she modeling?": "",
  "Tidal current circulation": "",
  "Coastal upwelling circulation": "",
  "Wind-driven surface circulation": "",
  "Thermohaline (density-driven) deep ocean circulation": "",
  "The student is modeling thermohaline circulation, which is driven by differences in water density caused by temperature and salinity variations. In her model, the cold, salty water sinks because it is denser, just as it does in the real ocean near the poles, driving the global deep ocean conveyor belt.": ""
}